The Science in Note-Taking or The Note-Taking in Science

As a double major, I noticed that in my mathematics courses there were a large amount of students with the physical coursebook and a notebook, even though we were provided with a free pdf of our coursebook. Whereas in my computer science courses I didnt see anybody with the physical coursebook or using a pen and notebook for note-taking.

During multiple lectures myself and two others observed students and recorded their note-taking habits over the lecture period. With this data I was hoping to find patterns amongst the different science based courses and find out if the faculty was an influential factor to differing note-taking methods across the courses.

More Methods, More Madness?

Firstly, well take a look at how many methods students in each course are using to take notes.

plot3

From this we can tell that students in MATHS130 are more likely to use more than one method for note-taking during lectures, whereas in the other three courses students are likely to stick to one method of note-taking during the lecture.

Pick Your Fighter

What are the different methods these students are using across the courses?

plot2

The methods used across the courses are varied, however there does exist dominating methods in each course. We can find that Laptops are dominating in BIOSCI338, pen & paper is dominating in MATHS130, tablets dominating in CHEM351, and a mix of both laptop & tablets being used mainly in COMPSCI220.

PDF or PEN?

Now well focus on which courses had students that were more reliant on technology for note-taking, and if there still exists courses with more students using pen and paper for note-taking.

plot1

We can see that 3/4 of these courses seem to be heavily technology reliant for note-taking, whereas in MATHS130 weve still got around 50% of students using a pen & paper as their main form of note-taking.
